issue.title: Support math operators in BeatmapAttributeText
issue.body:
- Answers https://github.com/ppy/osu/discussions/31901

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b7d5cc68-c2a0-4fc9-aad8-83dde7da637c

Adds support for:

- addition (+)
- subtraction (-)
- minus (-) (subtraction: x-y, minus: x+-y)
- multiplication (*)
- division (/)
- remainder (%)
- round brackets (())
- implied multiplication ((x+1)(x-1))

Title, Artist, DifficultyName, Creator, and Source usage will result the calculation not be calculated. Any error or typo will result in the calculation not happening.

In a follow up PR I plan to add function (abs(), sqrt(), root(), pow(), floor(), etc.) support. And no, I am not gonna add support for the use of | as absolute because then one third or more of this PR's line changes would have been about this operator.

issue.title: RFC: `@[override_repr]` attribute

labels.name: RFC
labels.description: Request for comments

labels.name: P-medium
labels.description: We may work on this issue if we find the time

issue.body:
### Proposal

Add an attribute that allows overriding the representation of an inductive type. All projections, constructors and `casesOn` should then become noncomputable by default; this should be overridable by `@[implemented_by]` and friends though. However, `@[implemented_by]` and friends should *not* work when the inductive type wasn't declared with `@[override_repr]`.

**Motivation:**

In some cases there are two representations of a type: one that works well for proofs and another that works well at runtime but doesn't allow for proofs. Infinite lists are an example of this:
```lean-4
-- works well for proofs but inefficient
def InfiniteList (Œ± : Type u) := Nat ‚Üí Œ±

-- works well at runtime but is formally an empty type
inductive InfiniteList (Œ± : Type u) where
  | cons (x : Œ±) (l : Thunk (InfiniteList Œ±))
```
The `@[override_repr]` attribute would then allow specifying a "model implementation" of a type for proofs and using another type for runtime:
```lean-4
inductive InfiniteListImpl (Œ± : Type u) where
  | cons (x : Œ±) (l : Thunk (InfiniteList Œ±))

@[override_repr InfiniteListImpl]
structure InfiniteList (Œ± : Type u) where
  get : Nat ‚Üí Œ±
```
Since `InfiniteListImpl` is now used as the representation of `InfiniteList`, the usual implementation of `InfiniteList.mk` and `InfiniteList.get` doesn't make any sense anymore (since it relied on the representation being the one of `InfiniteList`). Thus they should become noncomputable by default. However, you should then be able to override this by specifying your own implementation:
```lean-4
def InfiniteListImpl.get {Œ± : Type u} (l : InfiniteListImpl Œ±) (n : Nat) : Œ± :=
  match n, l with
  | 0, .cons x t => x
  | k + 1, .cons x t => t.get.get k

unsafe def InfiniteList.getImpl {Œ± : Type u} (l : InfiniteList Œ±) (n : Nat) : Œ± := (unsafeCast l : InfiniteListImpl Œ±).get n

attribute [implemented_by InfiniteList.getImpl] InfiniteList.get
```
Overriding projections (and constructors) only makes sense with `@[override_repr]` though; as such it should be forbidden for regular inductives and point to `@[override_repr]`:
```lean-4
structure InfiniteList (Œ± : Type u) where
  get : Nat ‚Üí Œ±

unsafe def InfiniteList.getImpl {Œ± : Type u} (l : InfiniteList Œ±) (n : Nat) : Œ± := (unsafeCast l : InfiniteListImpl Œ±).get n

/-
invalid implemented_by: target is a projection of InfiniteList but InfiniteList doesn't have an `@[override_repr]` attribute.
-/
attribute [implemented_by InfiniteList.getImpl] InfiniteList.get
```

Another use case is a simpler definition of `Erased` that has good reduction properties:
```lean-4
@[override_repr True]
structure Erased (Œ± : Sort u) where
  out : Œ±
```
Specifying `True` here should make the representation into the same of `True`: `‚óæ` (erased). The behavior should then also match what you'd expect from `Erased`: `Erased.out` is noncomputable and `Erased.mk` would be noncomputable but is erased anyways so works similarly to proofs.

### Community Feedback

https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/270676-lean4/topic/RFC.3A.20.60.40.5Boverride_repr.5D.60.20attribute/with/530131350

### Impact

Add :+1: to [issues you consider important](https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+sort%3Areactions-%2B1-desc). If others benefit from the changes in this proposal being added, please ask them to add :+1: to it.

Yeah, it might also be better to include explicit conversions for the compiler (especially in the base phase, where types are still available)

issue.title: Use parallel gzip compression via host pigz

labels.name: build/scripts/tools
labels.description: pull request/issues for build, scripts and tools related changes

issue.body:
[pigz](https://www.zlib.net/pigz) is a drop-in/fully functional replacement for `gzip` that exploits multiple processors and multiple cores when compressing data. To enable it, a new option has been introduced under:
```
Target Images > Use pigz for parallel gzip compression
```
which serves as an opt-in to insure that users wanting reproducible builds are not surprised by different checksum values when building on their own (see: https://openwrt.org/docs/guide-developer/security#reproducible_builds). This assume that the build bot farm will be using single-threaded `gzip` and not `pigz` for compression.

Additionally several `.mk` files have been modified to selectively use `pigz` to accomplish compression tasks.

Value proposition of using `pigz` is a speed up appox 10-20x when the build system compresses my standard `openwrt-x86-64-generic-ext4-combined.img` which is 962 MB total size with 192 MB kernel partition + 768 MB rootfs partition with 34% of data/the rest of the partitions being empty space.

Time to compress the image on...
AMD Ryzen 9950X processor (16C/32T)
* using `gzip -9`: approx 20 sec
* using `pigz -9`: approx 1 sec

AMD Ryzen 5 7600 processor (6C/12T)
* using `gzip -9`: approx 24 sec
* using `pigz -9`: approx 2 sec

Another test was running `make` after having already built all the packages which effectively just recreates the images after checking that everything is built. Here the speed up was a modest 37% increase.

On the AMD Ryzen 9950X processor (16C/32T)
* Using `gzip` (no `pigz` on the host system), the total process took 1 m 38 sec
* Using `pigz`, the total process took approx 1 m 2 sec

The PR has been tested both with and without `pigz` on the host system, in both cases the build of `r30780-9736d4214128` (with this PR applied) finished successfully.

Build system: x86/64
Build-tested: x86/64-glibc
Run-tested: x86/64-glibc (Intel N150 based box)

- Switch to warning on non-DAG structure, rather than non-forest structure of calculation graph in exploded FERC 1 tables.

Adjacent to #4482 

# Testing

- Ran full ETL locally and it failed because of the bad ENUM values.

## Tasks

- [ ] Address the ENUM values that were previously getting quietly nulled.
- [ ] Review the PR yourself and call out any questions or issues you have.
